# CLAUDE.md Templates for SonarQube Integration

Two templates are provided below. Copy the one that matches your desired
workflow into your project's `CLAUDE.md` (or `~/.claude/CLAUDE.md` for
global application).

---

## Template A — Minimal (Phase 1 / Phase 2)

Suitable for teams starting out. Adds a verification gate without requiring
guidelines to be fetched automatically.

```markdown
# SonarQube Integration

## Code Quality Gate

Before finalising any source file you have created or modified:

1. Run `run_advanced_code_analysis` on the file.
2. If any issues are found at BLOCKER, CRITICAL, or MAJOR severity, fix them.
3. Re-run analysis to confirm the fixes are clean.
4. Do not declare a task complete until all modified files pass with no
   BLOCKER, CRITICAL, or MAJOR issues.

When fixing an issue, use the rule key from the analysis result to look up
the rule documentation for specific guidance.
```

---

## Template B — Full (Phase 3 — Autonomous Guide-Generate-Verify Loop)

For teams that want the full automated loop. Claude will guide itself through
the complete workflow without prompting.

```markdown
# SonarQube Integration — Autonomous Mode

## Before Writing Any Code

When implementing a new feature, adding a class, or making a significant
change to an existing class:

1. Call `get_guidelines` with:
   - `mode: "combined"`
   - `categories`: relevant categories for the code being written (e.g.,
     "Code Complexity & Maintainability", "Naming Conventions & Code Style",
     "Exception/Error Handling", "Type System & Generics" for Java utility classes)
   - `languages`: the language of the files being modified (e.g., `["java"]`)

   Use the returned guidelines to inform code generation. Do not generate
   code that violates rules flagged as BLOCKER or CRITICAL in the guidelines.

2. When adding to or modifying an existing class, call the relevant
   architecture tools to understand the context:
   - `get_current_architecture(depth=1)` — understand package-level structure
   - `get_type_hierarchy(fqn)` — understand what extends/implements the class
   - `get_references(fqn)` — understand who uses the class (blast radius)

   Follow existing patterns in the codebase rather than inventing new ones.

## After Writing or Modifying Any Source File

After every source file modification (not just at the end of a task):

1. Call `run_advanced_code_analysis` on the modified file with:
   - `filePath`: the project-relative path (e.g., `src/main/java/.../MyClass.java`)
   - `branchName`: the current git branch
   - `fileScope`: `["MAIN"]` for production code, `["TEST"]` for test files

2. If issues are found:
   a. For each issue, note the rule key (e.g., `java:S1172`)
   b. Fix the issue in the source file
   c. Re-run `run_advanced_code_analysis` on the same file
   d. Repeat until the file has no BLOCKER, CRITICAL, or MAJOR issues

3. Only proceed to the next file after the current file is clean.

## Completion Criteria

Never declare a task complete until:
- All source files created or modified in this task have been analysed
- None of them have BLOCKER, CRITICAL, or MAJOR issues
- The final analysis run shows a clean result for every modified file

Report the final issue count (zero) when declaring the task complete.
```

---

## Notes on Customisation

### Adjusting severity thresholds

Both templates use BLOCKER/CRITICAL/MAJOR as the "must fix" threshold.
Adjust this to match your team's standards:
- Strict: also fix MINOR issues
- Lenient: only fix BLOCKER and CRITICAL

### Scoping guidelines fetches

The `categories` parameter in `get_guidelines` accepts any of these values:
- `"Code Complexity & Maintainability"`
- `"Naming Conventions & Code Style"`
- `"Exception/Error Handling"`
- `"Type System & Generics"`
- `"Serialization & Collections API"`
- `"Testing Practices & Coverage"`
- `"REST API Development"`
- `"Authentication & Authorization"`
- `"Web Security (XSS, CSRF, Injection)"`
- `"Logging & Monitoring"`
- (full list in the SonarQube MCP documentation)

Choosing relevant categories produces more targeted guidelines and faster
tool responses.

### Project-specific additions

Add any project-specific conventions below the template sections. For example:
- Package naming conventions
- Required imports or banned APIs
- Custom checkstyle rules not covered by SonarQube
```
